Dear Amit Singh, Thank you for your patience and for following the instructions to execute your JavaScript code in the VPL environment. It seems the issue persists despite the script adjustments for the NODE_PATH environment variable. This suggests that there might be another underlying issue at play. You can explore additional debugging steps: Environment Check: Although the provided script should correctly set the NODE_PATH, it's worth manually verifying the environment variables within the jail server to ensure they are set as expected. You can do this by adding debug statements in your `vpl_run.sh` script to print out environment variables to the console. Resource Limits: The issue might also be related to resource limits within the VPL environment. It's possible that the compilation of the evaluation program exceeds the available memory, causing it to terminate. To diagnose this, you can temporarily increase the resource limits for your VPL activity and see if the problem persists. Direct Execution Test: As a more direct test, you can attempt to execute your JavaScript code directly in the jail environment without using the VPL execution scripts. This can help determine if the issue is with the VPL setup or the code itself. To facilitate this, a simple C program like the following can grant you access to the jail command line, enabling you to run the JavaScript code manually and observe any immediate feedback or errors. Set the file with the following code as first file in your submissions. 
```text
#include <stdlib.h>
int main() {
    system("/bin/bash");
    return 0;
}
```
 Please, attempt these steps and share any findings. Best regards, Juan Carlos

